Our comparison with the results of finite element simulations will show that, for each choice of γ and λ, there is a range of ϵ in which both the FOSD and Frostig descriptions inaccurately represent the stress field over a large part of the sandwich. More precisely, for each choice of γ and λ, we have found a quite well-defined range ℰ ⊂ (0, 1) of values of ϵ, i.e.
(5)E={εsuchthat0<eant≤ε≤ed S V<1}
such that if ϵ > edSV, the stress state is effectively estimated by the FOSD modelling in any sandwich cross section at a distance larger than d = ωh from concentrated loads, with ω ≈ 1, or a bit larger, while for ϵ < eant, the Frostig theory becomes accurate in computing the stress state, still at a distance larger than ωh from the concentrated loads. The zig-zag modelling, endowed with the Jourawski-like post-processing for the shear stress evaluation proposed in Bardella and Tonelli [9], will be shown to be able to well represent the reference finite element solution for any ϵ ≥ eant. Hence, the combination of the Frostig and zig-zag models can cover all the relevant choices of sandwich heterogeneity ℋ. However, FOSD models remain extremely important because they are the simplest ones and their limit of validity coincides with that of Saint-Venant's principle.
